ties       = 23<!--Do not change this number without providing a reliable source--> (including the perpetrator)<ref name=\"CBC10\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/portapique-shooting-memorials-april-21-1.5539894|title=22 victims confirmed dead in N.S. mass shooting|publisher=CBC News|first=Taryn|last=Grant|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n| injuries         = 3\n| victim           = \n| perp             = Gabriel Wortman\n| numparts         = \n| numpart          = \n| dfens            = \n| dfen             = \n| footage          = \n| motive           = Unknown (under investigation)\n}}\nOn April 18 and 19, 2020, Gabriel Wortman committed [[Spree killer|multiple shootings]] and [[Arson|set fires]] at several locations in the [[Provinces and territories of Canada|Canadian province]] of [[Nova Scotia]]. Twenty-two <!--Do not change this number without providing a reliable source-->people died and three others were injured before the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] (RCMP) shot and killed Wortman at a gas station in [[Enfield, Nova Scotia|Enfield]].<ref name=\"CBC10\"/><ref name=\"CBC4\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killing-shooting-victims-remembered-1.5538032|title=22 victims of N.S. rampage include retirees, pregnant health care worker, veteran|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref>\n\nFor part of the thirteen hour-long crime spree, Wortman [[police impersonation|impersonated a police officer]] by driving a replica [[police car]] and wearing a police uniform. Authorities have yet to establish a motive for the killings; however, it is not being considered as an act of [[terrorism]], and an investigation is underway.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\"Politico\">{{cite news|last=Blatchford|first=Andy|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/19/at-least-10-dead-in-canadian-shooting-rampage-195506|title=Gunman kills at least 16, including officer, in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020 |work=[[Politico]]}}</ref> Wortman did not possess a [[possession and acquisition licence|firearms licence]], and it has not yet been determined how he acquired his weapons.<ref name=\"illegalweap\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kelownanow.com/news/news/National_News/Police_have_good_idea_guns_used_in_Nova_Scotia_mass_shooting_were_not_licensed/|title=Police have 'good idea' guns used in Nova Scotia mass shooting were not licensed|website=KelownaNow|language=en|date=April 23, 2020|access-date=April 23, 2020 |author=Canadian Press}}</ref><ref name=\"illegalweap2\">{{cite news|last=Lamoureux|first=Mack|url=https://www.vice.com/en_ca/article/3a83av/nova-scotia-gunman-was-not-a-legal-firearms-owner-rcmp-says|title=Nova Scotia Gunman Was Not a Legal Firearms Owner, RCMP Says|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020|work=Vice}}</ref> \n\nPolice were criticized for not using [[Alert Ready]] to warn the public about the killings, and an investigation into that decision has also begun.<ref name=\"CBC5\">{{cite news|last=Gorman|first=Michael|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/ns-public-alert-1.5538286|title=N.S. premier not ready to question if a public alert should have been issued about gunman|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|publisher=CBC News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421083535/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/ns-public-alert-1.5538286|archive-date=April 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC7\">{{cite news|last=Tasker|first=John Paul|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/questions-remain-rcmp-ns-emergency-alert-1.5540100|title=Questions emerge about RCMP's failure to send emergency alert on gunman's rampage|publisher=CBC News|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe rampage is the deadliest in [[Canadian history]], surpassing the 1989 [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique massacre]] in which 15 people were killed.<ref name=\"AP\">{{cite news|last=Gillies|first=Rob|url=https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|title=16 killed in shooting rampage, deadliest in Canadian history|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202425/https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|archive-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\n==Events==\n===April 18===\nThe incidents began as a case of [[domestic violence]] between Wortman and his girlfriend in the rural beachside community of [[Portapique]], {{convert|130|km|mi}} north of [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]].<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|last1=Stephenson|first1=Mercedes|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6858994/nova-scotia-shootings-gunman-attacked-girlfriend/|title=Nova Scotia shootings began after gunman attacked his girlfriend, sources say|date=April 23, 2020|work=Global News|access-date=April 23, 2020|url-status=live|last2=Armstrong|first2=James|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200423203801/https://globalnews.ca/news/6858994/nova-scotia-shootings-gunman-attacked-girlfriend/|archive-date=April 23, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-shooting-rcmp-investigation-press-conference-live-1.5542859|title=Gunman's resemblance to police officer made chase dangerous and complicated, says RCMP|date=April 24, 2020|work=CBC News|access-date=April 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> After an argument at a nearby party, he attacked her at his house and she fled into the woods. He lit his house on fire, then returned to the party house and began shooting, killing seven people.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":10\">{{cite news|last=Nardi|first=Christopher|url=https://nationalpost.com/news/canada/nova-scotia-schooter-gabriel-wortman-had-a-domestic-dispute-with-girlfriend-before-going-on-a-killing-spree|title=N.S. mass murderer's uniform, cruiser let him kill at will. He looked like one of us, RCMP say|date=April 24, 2020|accessdate=April 24, 2020|publisher=National Post}}</ref>\n\nBeginning at around 10:26 p.m., a number of Portapique residents called [[9-1-1]] to report gunshots and several fires.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|last=CBC News|first=|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-new-details-timeline-nova-scotia-manhunt-1.5541561|title=RCMP give new details on timeline of manhunt for N.S. shooter|date=April 22, 2020|publisher=CBC News|access-date=April 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|title=Nova Scotia mass killings: What we know and what we don't know|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420034520/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|archive-date=April 20, 2020 |publisher=CBC News}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"NBC\">{{cite news|last1=Madani|first1=Doha|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/canadian-authorities-say-mass-shooting-suspect-may-have-been-disguised-n1187381|title=16 dead in Nova Scotia shooting, Canadian authorities say|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=NBC News|last2=Stelloh|first2=Tim}}</ref> When RCMP officers arrived on the scene twelve minutes later, they discovered three burning houses on Orchard Beach Drive and Portapique Beach Road, and thirteen dead who had been shot inside and outside of the homes while fleeing the fires; police said many of them had died while trying to help other victims.<ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Tasker|first=John Paul|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/nova-scotia-tick-tock-murder-rampage-1.5539000|title='Those scars will never heal': piecing together a gunman's murderous rampage in Nova Scotia|date=April 20, 2020|access-date=April 21, 2020|url-status=live|publisher=CBC News}}</ref> One officer reported by radio that they could not locate any armed suspects, and that \"it's very bad what's going on down here\".<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\"CBC9\">{{cite news|last=Gatehouse|first=Jonathon|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/nova-scotia-shooting-manhunt-details-1.5542025|title='They don't know if they've caught him': Recordings reveal chaos of Nova Scotia manhunt|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"ABC\">{{cite news|last=Deliso|first=Meredith|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/multiple-victims-canada-shooting-suspect-dressed-police-officer/story?id=70232582|title=16 dead, including police officer, in deadliest shooting in Canadian history|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=ABC News}}</ref><ref name=\":5\" />\n\nFirst responders also found a man who said he had been shot and injured by someone driving what appeared to be a police car. The victim said the shooter had proceeded toward the beach, which was a [[Dead end (street)|dead end]].<ref name=\":8\" /> At 11:32 p.m., the RCMP posted a [[Twitter|tweet]] asking residents of the Portapique area to stay inside with their doors locked, as officers set up a search perimeter. There was confusion over whether a suspect had been apprehended and if the driver of the apparent police car was responsible, but as the investigation developed overnight, police determined that the perpetrator had eluded them.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\"CBC9\" />\n\n===April 19===\nBy the morning of April 19, police said they were dealing with an [[active shooter]] situation.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"MassLive\">{{cite news|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/2020/04/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman-kills-16-including-police-officer-in-canadas-deadliest-shooting-attack.html|title=Nova Scotia shooting: Gabriel Wortman kills 16 including police officer in Canada's deadliest shooting attack|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|website=MassLive}}</ref> At 6:30 a.m., police located Wortman's girlfriend, who confirmed that he was impersonating a police officer and provided them with a photo of his replica police vehicle.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":8\" />\n\nAt around 8:00 a.m., a 9-1-1 caller reported an explosion and gunfire at a house on Hunter Road in [[Wentworth, Nova Scotia|Wentworth]], approximately {{convert|37|km|mi}} north of Portapique. The two residents were killed, as was a neighbour who went to render assistance. At 9:35 a.m., another victim was shot and killed while walking in the community of [[Wentworth Valley]], on the road back south to Portapique.<ref name=\"CBC4\" /><ref name=\":8\" />\n\nRCMP publicly identified Wortman as the suspect at 8:54 a.m., and in a tweet posted at 10:17, they warned that he was impersonating a police officer and shared the photo of his vehicle.<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\">{{cite news|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shot-and-killed-by-police-1.4902687|title=At least 18 people killed in N.S. shooting; deadliest such attack in Canada: police|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020 |publisher=CTV News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Shah|first=Maryam|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6840120/nova-scotia-shooting-timeline/|title=Timeline: What we know about the Nova Scotia shooting spree|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020 |publisher=Global News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|title=A timeline of the deadly shooting incident in Nova Scotia|last1=Neustaeter|first1=Brooklyn|last2=Lopez-Martinez|first2=Melissa|date=April 19, 2020 |publisher=CTV News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420053707/https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|archive-date=April 20, 2020|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|title=RCMP officer among the dead after Nova Scotia gunman's rampage|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419130936/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|archive-date=April 19, 2020 |publisher=CBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/n-s-shooter-handcuffed-assaulted-his-girlfriend-before-mass-killing-1.4908549|title=N.S. shooter handcuffed, assaulted his girlfriend before mass killing|publisher=CTV News|last1=Battis|first1=Todd|last2=Cousins|first2=Ben|last3=Flanagan|first3=Ryan|date=April 23, 2020|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref> \n\nBeginning at 10:04 a.m., Wortman was seen in or near [[Glenholme, Nova Scotia|Glenholme]], [[Debert]], [[Onslow, Nova Scotia|Onslow]], and [[Brookfield, Nova Scotia|Brookfield]], indicating that he was travelling south toward Halifax.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-timeline-of-nova-scotia-mass-shooting/|title=Timeline of Nova Scotia mass shooting|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020|work=The Globe and Mail}}</ref> During this time, he performed two [[Traffic stop|traffic stops]] on random cars and killed their occupants.<ref name=\"CNN\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":10\" /> At one point, surveillance video apparently captured Wortman pulling into a parking lot in [[Millbrook 27|Millbrook First Nation]] in the mock police vehicle, briefly getting out to put on a reflective vest, and then driving off.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Boynton|first=Sean|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6855907/nova-scotia-mass-shooting-new-video/|title=Video appears to show Nova Scotia shooting suspect stop, change clothes amid killing spree|date=April 22, 2020|publisher=Global News|access-date=April 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSometime before 10:49 a.m., an RCMP officer driving north on Route 2 through [[Shubenacadie, Nova Scotia|Shubenacadie]] passed Wortman, who shot and injured the officer. He next encountered RCMP Constable Heidi Stevenson, whose cruiser he crashed into.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\"CBC9\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/04/20/nova-scotia-shooting-details-emerge-in-gabriel-wortmans-rampage/|title=Nova Scotia shooting: Details emerge in suspect Gabriel Wortman's rampage|last=Sheehy|first=Kate|date=April 20, 2020|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-shooting-community-reaction-1.5538181|title=Death toll from Nova Scotia gunman's rampage climbs to 19|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200421083535/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-shooting-community-reaction-1.5538181|archive-date=April 21, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref> Wortman exited his car and shot Stevenson, killing her, before taking her sidearm and ammunition.<ref name=\":10\" /> He then set both cars on fire.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\"CBC9\" /><ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\":11\">{{cite news|last1=Donkin|first1=Karissa|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/investigation-firearms-ns-shooting-1.5544180|title=Some of N.S. gunman's weapons came from U.S., police say|publisher=CBC News|date=April 24, 2020|accessdate=April 24, 2020}}</ref> Wortman then shot and killed a nearby motorist, and drove off in her silver [[Chevrolet Tracker (Americas)|Chevy Tracker]] [[Sport utility vehicle|SUV]].<ref name=\":10\" /> Police confirmed the vehicle change at 11:06 a.m.<ref name=\"CBC2\" />\n\nShortly thereafter, Wortman killed another victim at their Shubenacadie home and stole that person's [[Mazda3|Mazda 3]].<ref name=\"CBC2\" /> By 11:24 a.m., he was seen continuing south along [[Nova Scotia Highway 102|Highway 102]] through [[Milford (Halifax), Nova Scotia|Milford]].<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CBC9\" /><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|title=Canada shooting: Gunman kills at least 18 in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419211041/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|archive-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=BBC News}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{cite news|last1=McMillan|first1=Elizabeth|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/gunman-restrained-girlfriend-stole-victim-vehicle-ns-1.5543194|title=Girlfriend of N.S. gunman was among his victims, but she survived|date=April 23, 2020|accessdate=April 23, 2020|publisher=CBC News|last2=Hounsell|first2=Kayla}}</ref>\n\nFinally, thirteen hours after police began pursuing him, at 11:26 a.m., Wortman pulled into the [[Irving Oil#Big Stops|Irving Big Stop]] [[Rest area|service area]] in [[Enfield, Nova Scotia|Enfield]], {{convert|92|km|mi}} south of Portapique and {{convert|40|km|mi}} north of Halifax.<ref name=\"CBC9\" /> At least one RCMP officer who was already there to fill up on gas recognized Wortman, and shot and killed him.<ref name=\":7\" /> Wortman's death was confirmed by police at 11:40 a.m.<ref name=\"Vox\">{{cite news|last=Collins|first=Sean|url=https://www.vox.com/world/2020/4/19/21227349/mass-shooting-nova-scotia-canada-enfield-portapique|title=What we know about a mass shooting in Nova Scotia, Canada|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|website=Vox}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\" />\n\n==Victims==\nWortman killed 22<!--Do not change this number without providing a reliable source--> people, including Constable Stevenson. The other officer he shot survived, as did the person he shot in Portapique.<ref name=\"CBC10\" /><ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"global-news-rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s\">{{Cite news|last=Quon|first=Alexander|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|title=17 dead, including one RCMP officer, after shooting spree in Portapique, N.S.|date=April 19, 2020|access-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202613/https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|archive-date=April 19, 2020 |publisher=[[Global News]]|last2=Stephenson|first2=Mercedes}}</ref> Thirteen dead were found in Portapique, four in Wentworth, two in Debert, and three in Shubenacadie.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52376547|title=Canada shooting: Death toll in Nova Scotia rises to 22|publisher=BBC News|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422000411/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52376547|archive-date=April 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> They are believed to have died from gunshot wounds, but other causes are also being investigated.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"BBC\" /> Two dogs belonging to three killed victims survived being shot.{{cn}}\n\nAccording to Commissioner [[Brenda Lucki]], some of Wortman's first victims were closely connected to him, but as he continued, those he attacked became more random.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /> ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' reported that one victim at the home in Wentworth had previously gone hunting with Wortman, while [[CBC News]] reported that another victim owned the property in Portapique that was subject to a dispute between Wortman and his uncle.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite news|last=Donkin|first=Karissa|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/portapique-property-dispute-1.5542739|title=Victim of N.S. mass shooting owned a property involved in dispute between suspect, his uncle|date=23 April 2020|work=CBC News|access-date=23 April 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200424025555/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/portapique-property-dispute-1.5542739|archive-date=April 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Perpetrator==\n[[File:Atlantic Denture Clinic (3).jpg|thumb|Workers removing signage from the perpetrator's denture clinic in Dartmouth on April 22]]\n\nThe RCMP identified the perpetrator as 51-year-old Gabriel Wortman,<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.halifaxexaminer.ca/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/Wortman-Assault-conviction.pdf|format=PDF|accessdate=April 24, 2020|date=April 21, 2020|publisher=Halifax Examiner|title=Wortman assault conviction document (2002)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.halifaxexaminer.ca/featured/there-are-22-victims-in-the-weekend-murder-spree/|title=There are 22 victims in the weekend murder spree|accessdate=April 24, 2020|date=April 21, 2020|publisher=Halifax Examiner}}</ref> a [[denturist]] working in the Halifax area. He owned real estate in Portapique and [[Dartmouth, Nova Scotia|Dartmouth]].<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-gunman-profile-quiet-gentle-denturist|title=Nova Scotia shooting: shock and surprise at killings by denturist|first=Leyland|last=Cecco|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|website=The Guardian}}</ref> He attended [[Riverview High School (New Brunswick)|Riverview High School]] in [[New Brunswick]] and aspired to be a police officer, his [[yearbook]] entry alluding to this.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/just-unbelievable-neighbours-of-nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shocked-by-news-1.4903021|title='Just unbelievable': Neighbours of Nova Scotia shooting suspect shocked by news|date=April 19, 2020|publisher=CTV News|language=en|access-date=April 20, 2020|last=Frisko|first=Bruce}}</ref> \n\nWortman pleaded guilty to assault in 2002 and was sentenced to nine months of probation, in which he was prohibited from possessing weapons and ordered to undergo anger management counselling.<ref name=\"CTV6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/n-s-rcmp-say-they-were-in-process-of-preparing-alert-when-gunman-was-killed-1.4906672|title=N.S. RCMP say they were 'in process' of preparing alert when gunman was killed|publisher=CTV News|last=Flanagan|first=Ryan|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC8\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-criminal-record-1.5541176|title=Suspect in N.S. killings didn't have criminal record, but previously pleaded guilty to a crime|publisher=CBC News|last=Donkin|first=Karissa|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref> \n\nHe was also involved in two civil matters regarding property disputes, according to interviews and public records. In 2004, he offered to help a friend who had financial difficulties and was about to lose his house, then discreetly took ownership of the house, evicted the man and sold the property. In 2015, his uncle lent him a house while selling his [[Edmonton]] condominium. Wortman refused to release the Portapiqe property back to him, claiming he was owed money, until the uncle eventually sold it; one of the buyers later became a victim.<ref name=\"CBC8\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6846920/nova-scotia-killer-financial-practices/|title='He stole my house': Nova Scotia killer had history of dubious financial practices|publisher=Global News|last1=Bell|first1=Stewart|last2=Russell|first2=Andrew|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWortman had a hobby of buying law enforcement [[memorabilia]] and refurbishing old police cruisers. One person called his home a \"shrine\" for the RCMP.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|title=Nova Scotia mass shooter was a denturist with an obsession for policing|work=[[The Globe and Mail]]|last1=Woo|first1=Andrew|last2=Mercer|first2=Greg|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420055810/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He stored the two old police cruisers that he bought behind his denture clinic.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"CTV5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/what-we-know-about-the-nova-scotia-rampage-suspect-1.4903920|title=What we know about the Nova Scotia rampage suspect|publisher=CTV News|last=Bogart|first=Nicole|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> According to a businessman in [[Dieppe, New Brunswick]], Wortman inquired about buying a decommissioned RCMP cruiser from him in 2017 or 2018, claiming to be a retired officer who wanted to park the vehicle outside his house to deter thieves. For price reasons, he did not buy it.<ref name=\":9\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia-killer-fake-cruiser-1.5543176|title=Nova Scotia gunman didn't hide his fake RCMP cruiser \u2014 even from police, says ex-boss|publisher=CBC News|last=Gatehouse|first=Jonathon|date=April 23, 2020|accessdate=April 23, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200424025555/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia-killer-fake-cruiser-1.5543176|archive-date=April 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nNeighbours said Wortman struggled with alcohol use and his business was negatively affected by the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nova Scotia]], which forced all non-essential denturist services to close.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAfter the killings, the decorative signage on Wortman's denture clinic on Portmouth Street in Dartmouth, portraying a large smile and a set of dentures, was the subject of complaints from the public. In response, [[Halifax Regional Police]] removed the signage on April 22.<ref name=\"signage\">{{cite news |last1=April |first1=Allan |title=Police remove teeth, signage from denture clinic owned by N.S. shooter |url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/police-remove-teeth-signage-from-denture-clinic-owned-by-n-s-shooter-1.4907452 |publisher=CTV News |date=April 22, 2020 |accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Investigations==\n===Criminal===\nNo motive has been established for the killings, though they are not considered an act of [[terrorism]].<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" />\n\nOn the afternoon of April 20, Chief Superintendent Chris Leather said there were 16 crime scenes, including five structure fires, over a distance of at least {{convert|50|km|mi}}. He said he expected the death toll to rise as these crime scenes are investigated.<ref name=\"CBC6\" />\n\nNova Scotia's [[Serious Incident Response Team]] announced it would conduct an investigation into the police shooting of Wortman, as well as another incident involving two RCMP officers who discharged their weapons inside a [[Fire station|fire hall]] in Onslow; Wortman was not there at the time.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref>{{cite press release |url=https://sirt.novascotia.ca/investigation-begins-enfield-death|title=INVESTIGATION BEGINS INTO ENFIELD DEATH|date=April 19, 2020|publisher=Serious Incident Response Team|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn the evening of April 21, the [[Canadian Armed Forces]] were dispatched to assist the RCMP in their investigation by providing them with additional personnel and supplies.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/military-equipment-nova-scotia-rcmp-investigation-mass-killing-1.5540743|title=Military personnel, equipment to aid RCMP investigation into mass killing|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref>\n\nLeather noted that Wortman's use of a police cruiser and wearing a police uniform allowed him to help evade detection for a long time. Owning police vehicles or uniforms is not a crime, but [[Police impersonation|impersonating a police officer]] is.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Donkin|first1=Karissa|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/ns-shooting-rcmp-vehicle-1.5539877|title=Police uniform, mock RCMP cruiser key parts of investigation into N.S. shootings|date=April 21, 2020|publisher=[[CBC News]]|access-date=April 22, 2020|last2=Daigle|first2=Thomas}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Hill|first=Brian|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6851700/nova-scotia-shooting-gunman-uniform-police-car|title=How a real uniform and replica police car helped the Nova Scotia gunman go undetected|date=April 22, 2020|publisher=[[Global News]]|access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref> CBC News reported that at least one RCMP officer had taken note of Wortman's replica vehicle, and advised him not to drive it on the road.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nThe man who Wortman had previously considered buying police car from said that he was warned by police during the incident that he was considered a possible target; however, he was ultimately not a victim, and police later refuted suggestions that Wortman had kept a written list of targets.<ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.citynews1130.com/2020/04/23/would-be-victim-nova-scotia-gunman-list-report/|title=Would-be victim reveals Nova Scotia gunman had 'list of people to target': report|last=Gul|first=Monika|date=April 23, 2020|website=CKWX|access-date=April 23, 2020}}</ref> \n\nLeather also said that Wortman had no [[Possession and acquisition licence|licence to own guns]] and that his weapons were illegally purchased, a matter that will be investigated further.<ref name=\"illegalweap\" /><ref name=\"illegalweap2\" /> ''[[Global News]]'' reported that a rifle, shotgun, and handgun were used in the shootings.<ref name=\":6\" /> Police later said one of the weapons had originated in Canada, but all of the others likely came from the [[United States]].<ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":11\" />\n\nThe Nova Scotia RCMP Major Crime Unit launched a tip hotline to gather further information about the killings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/rcmp-launch-tip-line-to-gather-information-about-weekend-mass-shooting-1.4908807|title=RCMP launch tip line to gather information about weekend mass shooting|date=April 23, 2020|first=Leigha |last=Farnell |publisher=CTV Atlantic |language=en|access-date=April 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Lack of emergency alert===\nFollowing questions about why Nova Scotia did not use [[Alert Ready]], Canada's emergency population warning system, to warn the public about the killings and instead used popular [[social media]] platforms Twitter and [[Facebook]] to provide updates, RCMP officials said they had been dealing with an unfolding situation and details kept being updated many times. However, the areas affected had poor cellular Internet service and were mostly populated by seniors who might not have used Twitter. Relatives of the victims pointed out that Alert Ready would have sent text messages advising residents of what was happening and to stay indoors, which could have saved lives.<ref name=\"CTV7\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/u-s-citizens-in-nova-scotia-were-sent-additional-warning-during-deadly-rampage-1.4907139|title=U.S. citizens in Nova Scotia were sent additional warning during deadly rampage|publisher=CTV News|last=Gilmore|first=Rachel|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Cooke|first=Alex|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-shooting-emergency-alert-1.5540220|title='I would not have let my wife leave': Widower blasts lack of emergency alert during N.S. shootings|date=April 21, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020|publisher=CBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/corrie-ellison-mass-shooting-brother-clinton-hiding-1.5541082|title=He was 'hunted' by the Portapique gunman and survived. His brother didn't|publisher=CBC News|last=Davie|first=Emma|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref> Chief Superintendent Leather said an investigation would be conducted into the decision-making process on alerting the public.<ref name=\"CBC5\" /><ref name=\"CBC7\" />\n\nOn April 22, Leather said officers in Dartmouth were asked by the province about a warning at 10:15 a.m., but did not agree on details like wording before Wortman died 71 minutes later.<ref name=\"CTV6\" /> The [[List of diplomatic missions of the United States|United States Consulate]] in Halifax said it emailed American citizens in Nova Scotia warning them of the situation using the RCMP's information.<ref name=\"CTV7\"/>\n\n==Aftermath==\n===Political reactions===\n[[File:Prime Minister Justin Trudeau - Remarks on the shooting in Portapique, Nova Scotia - 2020.webm|thumb|Prime Minister Trudeau's remarks on the killings (April 20)]]\n[[Prime Minister of Canada|Canadian Prime Minister]] [[Justin Trudeau]] expressed his condolences.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> During his morning address from [[Rideau Cottage]] on April 20, he reaffirmed his commitment to strengthening [[gun control]].<ref name=\"trudeauGun\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/trudeau-reiterates-gun-control-commitment-in-wake-of-mass-shooting-1.4903966|title=Trudeau reiterates gun control commitment in wake of mass shooting|publisher=CTV News|last=Gilmore|first=Rachel|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref> He asked the media to not use Wortman's name or image: \"Do not give this person the gift of infamy.\"<ref>{{cite news |author=Associated Press |url=https://www.kktv.com/content/news/Police-At-least-10-killed-in-shooting-rampage-in-Canada-569772421.html|title=Canada's worst mass shooting leaves at least 18 dead|website=kktv.com|publisher=KKTV|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200422085944/https://www.kktv.com/content/news/Police-At-least-10-killed-in-shooting-rampage-in-Canada-569772421.html|archive-date=April 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Nova Scotia Premier]] [[Stephen McNeil]] told reporters, \"This is one of the most senseless acts of violence in our province's history.\" He expressed his condolences to the residents affected and the families of the victims.<ref name=\"CTV2\">{{cite news|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/shooting-one-of-the-most-senseless-acts-of-violence-in-nova-scotia-s-history-premier-1.4902917|title=Shooting 'one of the most senseless acts of violence' in Nova Scotia's history: premier|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|publisher=CTV News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> \n\n[[Elizabeth II]], [[monarchy of Canada|Queen of Canada]], expressed her condolences, saying that she and [[Prince Philip]] were \"saddened by the appalling events\", and that her thoughts and prayers were with the people of Nova Scotia and all Canadians. She also paid tribute to the \"bravery and sacrifice\" of the RCMP and other emergency services.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-canada-crime-nova-scotia-britain/queen-elizabeth-sends-condolences-to-canada-after-nova-scotia-shooting-idUSKCN2231JF|title=Queen Elizabeth sends condolences to Canada after Nova Scotia shooting|accessdate=April 21, 2020|date=April 21, 2020|publisher=Reuters|last=Faulconbridge|first=Guy}}</ref>\n\nThe [[White House]] condemned the killings and expressed US President [[Donald Trump]] and First Lady [[Melania Trump]]'s condolences.<ref name=\"CNN\"/>\n\n===Memorials and fundraisers===\nFlags across Canada were lowered to [[half-mast]],<ref name=\"Guardian2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-friends-family-pay-tribute-victims|title=Nova Scotia shooting: friends and family pay tribute to 'beautiful souls' lost in rampage|work=The Guardian|last=Cecco|first=Leyland|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420223029/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-friends-family-pay-tribute-victims|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] observed a moment of silence for the victims.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/trudeau-nova-scotia-shooting-1.5538301| title='We're going to get through this together': Trudeau calls for unity after mass killing |publisher=CBC News| date=April 20, 2020| accessdate=April 20, 2020| url-status=live| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200421002715/https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/trudeau-nova-scotia-shooting-1.5538301| archive-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 20, the [[CN Tower]] was illuminated in blue and white, the colours of the [[Flag of Nova Scotia|Nova Scotia flag]], and also in RCMP red, blue, and gold in honour of Stevenson, on the quarter- and half-hours. On April 21, at [[Niagara Falls]], both the Canadian [[Horseshoe Falls]] and the [[American Falls]] were also illuminated in blue and white as a symbol of bi-national solidarity with Nova Scotia.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/iconic-canadian-symbols-glow-blue-and-white-in-show-of-solidarity-with-nova-scotia-1.4907477|title=Iconic Canadian symbols glow blue and white in show of solidarity with Nova Scotia|publisher=CTV News|last1=Jerrett|first1=Andrea|last2=Price|first2=Melanie|date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the days after the incident, many fundraisers for the victims and their families were started on the crowdfunding platform [[GoFundMe]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/n-s-rampage-victims-young-sons-hid-during-attack-family-member-says-1.4906956 |title=N.S. rampage victims' young sons hid during attack, family member says |publisher=[[CTV News]] |last1=Neustaeter |first1=Brooklyn |date=April 22, 2020 |accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC11\"/> There was also at least one fake or fraudulent fundraiser started, which was subsequently removed. Jeff Thomson of the RCMP's Anti-Fraud Centre warned Canadians to be diligent when donating to charities related to the tragedy.<ref name=\"CBC11\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/beware-of-fake-ns-shooting-charity-campaigns-rcmp-warns-1.5541570 |title=Fake N.S. shooting fundraiser leads to warning from RCMP |publisher=[[CBC News]] |last1=Colbert |first1=Yvonne |date=April 23, 2020 |accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs large gatherings are restricted in the province due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Canada|coronavirus pandemic]], a public virtual vigil aired on CBC Atlantic on April 24 at 7:00 p.m. [[Atlantic Time Zone|ADT]].<ref name=\"CBC12\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/virtual-vigil-facebook-22-victims-nova-scotia-shooting-1.5541093 |title=Virtual vigil honouring victims of N.S. shootings planned for Friday |publisher=[[CBC News]] |date=April 22, 2020|accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6852130/virtual-vigil-nova-scotia-shooting |title=How to watch the virtual vigil for the Nova Scotia shooting victims |publisher=[[Global News]] |last1=Goldfinger |first1=Daina |last2=Lieberman |first2=Caryn |date=April 22, 2020 |accessdate=April 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of massacres in Canada]]\n* [[List of rampage killers in the Americas]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist |refs=\n<ref name=\"CBC2\">\n{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|title=Timeline: How an active-shooter situation unfolded in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420001136/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|archive-date=April 20, 2020  |publisher=CBC News}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"CNN\">\n{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/20/americas/nova-scotia-shooting-monday/index.html|title=Gunman evaded police for nearly 12 hours and killed at least 18 in one of Canada's deadliest mass shootings|publisher=CNN|last1=McLaughlin|first1=Eliott C.|last2=Newton|first2=Paula|date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\">\n{{Cite news|last=Diaz|first=Johnny|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|title=Nova Scotia Shooting Kills at Least 16, Police Say|date=April 19, 2020|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419142013/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|archive-date=April 19, 2020|last2=Bilefsky|first2=Dan}}</ref>\n<ref name=\":5\">\n{{Cite news|last1=Mercer |first1=Greg |last2=Jones |first2=Lindsay |last3=Pruden |first3=Jana |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-shooter-acted-alone-during-rampage-rcmp-say/|title=RCMP defend not sending emergency alert before Nova Scotia gunman was killed |date=April 23, 2020|publisher=The Globe and Mail|access-date=April 23, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200423151005/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-shooter-acted-alone-during-rampage-rcmp-say/|archive-date=April 23, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/we-mourn-for-their-families-teacher-nurse-cancer-survivor-among-n-s-shooting-spree-victims-1.4903446 \"'We mourn for their families': Teacher, nurse, cancer survivor among N.S. shooting spree victims\"]. [[CTV News]]. April 20, 2020.\n\n[[Category:2020 crimes in Canada]]\n[[Category:2020 in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:2020 murders in North America]]\n[[Category:2020s mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:21st-century mass murder in North America]]\n[[Category:April 2020 crimes]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in the 2020s]]\n[[Category:Attacks on buildings and structures in 2020]]\n[[Category:Crime in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Death in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in Canada]]\n[[Category:Royal Canadian Mounted Police]]\n[[Category:Spree shootings in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "InedibleHulk", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eApril 18:Overcited.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nova_Scotia_killings"}
